  <entry>
    <id>https://community.sap.com/t5/technology-q-a/re-combining-data-from-multiple-apis-in-sap-build-apps/qaq-p/13893510/comment-id/4887473#M4887473</id>
    <title>Re: Combining Data from Multiple APIs in SAP Build Apps</title>
    <updated>2024-10-09T08:36:19.067000+02:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Dan_Wroblewski</name>
      <uri>https://community.sap.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/72</uri>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;P&gt;As I suggest to most people, I would create your own custom table -- not use the built-in table component. Building your own table is pretty easy and gives you COMPLETE control on how it works. If you need help with this let me know.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;Once you have your own table, handling the data becomes trivial. Get data 1 and data 2, then use a formula to combine the them into a page variable. Then connect the page variable to the "Repeat with" of your table row. And if you need help with this part, let me know.&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;In the future there may be templates that makes it even simpler. See this Devtoberfest session:&lt;/P&gt;&lt;P&gt;&lt;div class="video-embed-center video-embed"&gt;&lt;iframe class="embedly-embed" src="https://cdn.embedly.com/widgets/media.html?src=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fembed%2F4zVepzBgSmM%3Ffeature%3Doembed&amp;amp;display_name=YouTube&amp;amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.youtube.com%2Fwatch%3Fv%3D4zVepzBgSmM&amp;amp;image=https%3A%2F%2Fi.ytimg.com%2Fvi%2F4zVepzBgSmM%2Fhqdefault.jpg&amp;amp;type=text%2Fhtml&amp;amp;schema=youtube" width="200" height="112" scrolling="no" title="🟣 Develop Even Faster (!) with SAP Build Apps Templates" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; encrypted-media; picture-in-picture;" allowfullscreen="true"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/P&gt;</content>
    <link href="https://community.sap.com/t5/technology-q-a/re-combining-data-from-multiple-apis-in-sap-build-apps/qaq-p/13893510/comment-id/4887473#M4887473"/>
    <published>2024-10-09T08:36:19.067000+02:00</published>
  </entry>
  <entry>
    <id>https://community.sap.com/t5/technology-q-a/re-grant-users-read-only-access-to-the-context-of-a-sap/qaq-p/13893525/comment-id/4887476#M4887476</id>
    <title>Re: Grant users read-only access to the context of a sap...</title>
    <updated>2024-10-09T08:46:57.287000+02:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Dan_Wroblewski</name>
      <uri>https://community.sap.com/t5/user/viewprofilepage/user-id/72</uri>
    </author>
    <content>Silly me. I think if the API itself doesn't let you distinguish those 2 use cases, and the destination mechanism in the cockpit doesn't let you control access at the HTTP method level, then you are left with middleware (e.g., API Management or a CAP service). The only other way I can think of is if the original API had different URL paths between the GET and the POST but that is not the case. I had also thought of using the CSRF mechanism to block POST requests but I could not figure out how to get the flow to NOT handle CSRF but there may be a way.</content>
    <link href="https://community.sap.com/t5/technology-q-a/re-grant-users-read-only-access-to-the-context-of-a-sap/qaq-p/13893525/comment-id/4887476#M4887476"/>
    <published>2024-10-09T08:46:57.287000+02:00</published>
  </entry>
